OID - PIP: 009045
OID - POP: 00110034
OAB - The American Cancer Society estimates that 110,000 new cases of breast cancer 
      will be discovered in 1981. Breast cancer represents 27% of the cancers and 19% 
      of the cancer deaths in women. The incidence of breast cancer is slightly higher 
      for whites, but it has increased in blacks by 25%. The highest incidence of 
      breast cancer occurs after age 35, with 83% of the cases occurring after age 50 
      and only 1.5% under the age of 30. 1 in 11 women will develop breast cancer 
      sometime during their lifetime. There appears to be an increasing incidence of 
      breast cancer, but longer survival rates have helped to stabilize the mortality 
      rates over the past 50 years. Several factors have been associated with increased 
      risk for breast cancer, including demographic, anthropometric, dietary, 
      menstrual, reproductive, hormonal, genetic, and others, including a history of 
      benign breast disease. Descriptive epidemiology divides patients into high and 
      low risks. There is general agreement that there is a marked racial preference 
      for breast cancer in whites contrasted with Orientals living in the Orient. The 
      highest incidence of breast cancer in the U.S. is found in the northeastern part 
      of the country. Those countries with the lowest consumption of meat have the 
      lowest incidence of breast cancer. It should be noted that key risk factors such 
      as age at menarche and weight are determined by the diet and thus the diet must 
      be considered a fundamental risk factor. The woman with previous cancer of 1 
      breast is at risk for cancer in the opposite breast. A significantly higher risk 
      for breast cancer occurs in women with an earlier age at menarche. For several 
      years epidemiologists have noted the decreased risk associated with increased 
      parity and the increased risk of single women. Women whose natural menopause 
      occurs before age 45 have only half the breast cancer risk of those whose 
      menopause occurs after the age of 55. The most attractive hypotheses dealing with 
      breast cancer concern those related to endocrine factors, specifically 
      progesterone, prolactin, androgens, and estrogens. Several pieces of evidence 
      suggest that estrogens play an important part in determining the hormonal milieu 
      that favors the development of human breast cancer. Most investigators suggest 
      that estrogen is preparative rather than carcinogenic. Patients taking oral 
      contraceptives (OCs) are only now entering the age period when breast cancer is 
      most common. Studies regarding the use of postmenopausal estrogens and the 
      development of breast cancer do not clearly show any increased risk, but some 
      studies report that high doses for long periods of time may be associated with 
      increased risk. Postmenopausal replacement therapy should be given in the lowest 
      dose for the shortest possible period of time.
