TI  - Quality of breast-cancer care in Italian general hospitals.
PG  - 258-60
AB  - The diagnostic and therapeutic care and degree of follow-up delivered to 2406 
      breast-cancer patients over two years (1978-79) in 31 Italian hospitals are 
      reviewed. Although there was broad agreement about recommended treatment 
      protocols, staging by standard methods was recorded in only 44% of patients, 
      assessment and reporting of side-effects was considered in only 49% of all 
      treated patients, follow-up data at two years were available for only 54% of 
      living patients, and the dropout rate from chemotherapy protocols was 35%. 
      Improvement of these unsatisfactory aspects of care would allow a better 
      appreciation of the real benefit that could be achieved with recommended 
      protocols and would result in a more effective use of health resources.
