DP  - 1982 Aug
TI  - Nonestrogenic drugs and breast cancer.
PG  - 329-32
AB  - The relation between breast cancer and selected nonestrogenic drugs was evaluated 
      in the Group Health Cooperative of Puget Sound, Seattle, Washington, a prepaid 
      health care organization with computerized information on diagnoses and 
      outpatient drug use. No important positive associations with breast cancer were 
      found in a follow-up study of 302 women aged 35-74 years. These women were newly 
      diagnosed with breast cancer in 1977-1980 and were studied in relation to 
      exposure in the six months prior to diagnosis to one or more of the following 
      drugs: diazepam, digitalis glycosides, medroxyprogesterone acetate, methyldopa, 
      metronidazole, phenothiazines, tricyclic antidepressants, thiazides, 
      thyroid/levothyroxine sodium, or spironolactone. A modest association between 
      recent reserpine use and breast cancer was present (risk ratio = 1.7, 90% 
      confidence interval 0.9-3.3).
