DP  - 1990 Dec
TI  - Breast self-examination and the health belief model: variations on a theme.
PG  - 421-8
AB  - Variables derived from the Health Belief Model (HBM) were studied in relation to 
      breast self-examination (BSE) performance, which was measured in terms of both 
      frequency and thoroughness. Data were collected from 202 adult women via 
      self-administered questionnaires. Susceptibility and Seriousness were combined to 
      form a "threat of breast cancer" variable, and two approaches were used to 
      compute "net perceived efficacy of BSE." However, barriers and susceptibility in 
      their original form explained more variance in BSE practice than did the combined 
      variables. The negative relationship found between perceived barriers and BSE 
      performance (r = -.44) is consistent with previous findings. Implications for 
      research and practice are presented.
