DP  - 1984 Sep
TI  - Alcoholic beverage consumption and breast cancer in a French case-control study.
PG  - 350-7
AB  - An association between regular consumption of alcohol with meals and breast 
      cancer was found in a French case-control study of 1,010 women with breast cancer 
      and 1,950 women with nonmalignant diseases; the relative risk of breast cancer 
      for women drinking alcoholic beverages with meals compared with nondrinkers was 
      1.47 (p = 10(-4) allowing for classical risk factors. Detailed information on 
      alcohol consumption was obtained from 500 cases and 945 controls; the risks of 
      breast cancer were greater for women drinking beer and for women drinking wine 
      than for nondrinkers, and the risk increased with the amount of beer, of wine and 
      of total alcohol consumption in grams of pure alcohol.
