PMID- 6737359
OWN - NLM
STAT- MEDLINE
DCOM- 19840813
LR  - 20260128
IS  - 0035-8797 (Print)
IS  - 0035-8797 (Linking)
VI  - 34
IP  - 262
DP  - 1984 May
TI  - Breast cancer: views of general practitioners on its detection and treatment.
PG  - 250-4
AB  - A considerable proportion of women with breast cancer in this country present for 
      treatment in late stages of the disease; Britain's primary health-care system 
      means that in most cases the possible diagnosis of breast cancer is first made in 
      general practice. This offers ample opportunity for early diagnosis and a better 
      understanding about the way the general practitioners perceive the problems 
      associated with the disease. With that specific aim, the present article reports 
      on a survey conducted simultaneously in Oxford and in Edinburgh. Results show 
      that general practitioners in the survey are deeply concerned about breast cancer 
      and see a definite role for themselves in its early detection and long-term 
      management. They also see a need for more health education that includes the 
      encourgement of breast self-examination programmes. Most are in favour of 
      open-access breast clinics for women and, in general, they feel positive about 
      self-education programmes.
