VI  - 26
IP  - 3
DP  - 1990 Mar
TI  - Malignancies in families of women with medullary, tubular and invasive ductal 
      breast cancer.
PG  - 295-303
AB  - Breast cancer seems to represent a heterogeneous group of neoplasia originating 
      from the parenchymal epithelium of the mammary gland. Family studies combined 
      with genetic epidemiological analyses and histological evaluations were used to 
      gain an insight into this nosological entity. Special emphasis was given to the 
      type and frequency of neoplasia in close relatives. This study represents 
      pedigrees of 36 histologically defined pure tubular and 22 pure medullary breast 
      cancer patients as well as 171 with the invasive ductal form. The incidence of 
      cancer in the first degree relatives of all three groups is compared to that of 
      the local population. The first degree relatives did not have a higher risk (RR) 
      for the neoplastic diseases. However, breast cancer occurs more frequently in the 
      female relatives of all three groups. Other cancers have different relative 
      risks.
