IS  - 0163-8343 (Linking)
VI  - 10
IP  - 5
DP  - 1988 Sep
TI  - When the patient doesn't die.
PG  - 367-72
AB  - Little has been written about the effects on psychotherapy when a patient who is 
      expected to die survives. A young woman who was nearing the end of routine 
      psychotherapy was found to have breast cancer. There were two recurrences of the 
      malignancy, and while everything pointed toward a rapid death, the patient did 
      not die. Psychotherapy, which had begun before the diagnosis, continued during 
      intensive medical treatment and beyond. Some of the changes affecting both the 
      patient and the therapist are described, and some guidelines are suggested for 
      conducting psychotherapy with cancer patients who have prolonged survival.
