OID - PIP: 048323
OID - POP: 00185275
OAB - In this Norwegian case-control study, it was found that the relative risk of 
      getting breast cancer among women whose mothers had had this cancer is 3.7. The 
      data for this study was taken from all the 105 cases of breast cancer diagnosed 
      in Norway over a 1 year period in 1984-85. This was compared with a control group 
      of 210 picked randomly from the general population, which matched the test group 
      as to age, oral contraceptive usage, etc. Diagnostic and surgical records were 
      made available by the country's 71 surgical hospitals. It was stipulated that 
      patients could be contacted for interviews only by hospital physicians, and not 
      directly by the researchers. Altogether, 105 (92%) of those selected were 
      interviewed in this indirect manner. Results showed that in the test group, 10 
      subjects had mothers who had breast cancer, and 95 did not. In the control group, 
      95 had mothers with breast cancer and 204 had not, equalling a relative adjusted 
      risk rate of 3.7. It was also found that this risk increases until age 40, and 
      then declines significantly, which is consistent with other studies of this 
      correlation conducted in the United States. Iceland and Sweden It is still not 
      known what role genetic inheritance or commonality of environment play in this 
      disposition for mother-daughter breast cancer. At the present time, the women 
      with mothers who had breast cancer can do nothing to counter this risk. However, 
      they should be especially careful to get frequent medical examinations, since 
      early diagnosis can greatly improve prognosis.
