PMID- 2611041
OWN - NLM
STAT- MEDLINE
DCOM- 19900308
LR  - 20190903
IS  - 0284-186X (Print)
IS  - 0284-186X (Linking)
VI  - 28
IP  - 6
DP  - 1989
TI  - Flow cytometry DNA ploidy and number of cell populations in the primary breast 
      cancer and their correlation to the prognosis.
PG  - 913-8
AB  - In a prospective study on 516 breast cancer patients flow cytometry DNA ploidy 
      and number of cell populations (defined as number of DNA stem lines) detected in 
      the primary tumor were evaluated for prognostic purposes. The median follow-up 
      time was about 5 years. In the 241 node negative cases, those patients with three 
      or more cell populations had the worst prognosis, with a distant recurrence-free 
      survival rate of about 60% at five years compared to 90% in cases with only one 
      cell population detected in the primary tumor. The number of tumor involved 
      axillary lymph nodes was the outstanding prognostic indicator which was confirmed 
      in 275 node positive patients; DNA ploidy and number of cell populations did not 
      give any significant prognostic information in this group of patients.
