DP  - 1989 May
TI  - New biologic prognostic factors in breast cancer.
PG  - 49-54; discussion 58, 61, 64
AB  - Long-accepted prognostic factors for breast cancer patients include the number of 
      axillary lymph nodes positive for cancer; size of the primary; histopathologic 
      features such as nuclear grade, histologic grade, and mitotic index; and the 
      estrogen and progesterone receptor status. Unfortunately, these factors are 
      relatively insensitive in predicting which women are particularly at risk of 
      relapse. Newer discoveries which are or may be better prognosticators of a breast 
      cancer patient's future course include growth factors, oncogenes, thymidine 
      labeling index, and measurement of DNA ploidy status by flow cytometry.
