VI  - 36
IP  - 1
DP  - 1990 Jan
TI  - [Relationship of breast cancer and HLA in Japanese females].
PG  - 29-33
AB  - One hundred and thirty-seven female breast cancer patients have been HLA-typed by 
      a cytotoxicity test. Over all, no specific HLA antigen was found, though when the 
      patients were divided into two groups, i.e., into those with bilateral or 
      unilateral cancers, A24 and Cw7 was found to be significantly increased in the 
      bilateral group. Further, a haplotype of A24-Cw7 was frequently seen in the 
      bilateral group. No specific HLA antigen, however, was found in patients 
      stratified by a familial history of cancer. It thus was concluded that bilateral 
      breast cancer patients that have developed from patients with a unilateral cancer 
      are detectable by HLA typing.
