TI  - Immuno-electron microscopic identification of human estrogen receptor-DNA 
      complexes at the estrogen-responsive element and in the first intron of a Xenopus 
      vitellogenin gene.
PG  - 217-20
AB  - Using an extract of nuclei from the estrogen-responsive human breast cancer cell 
      line MCF-7, protein-DNA complexes were assembled in vitro at the 5' end of the 
      Xenopus laevis vitellogenin gene B2 that is normally expressed in liver after 
      estrogen induction. The complexes formed were analyzed by electron microscopy 
      after labeling by the indirect colloidal gold immunological method using a 
      monoclonal antibody specific for the human estrogen receptor. As identified by 
      its interaction with protein A-gold, the antibody was found linked to two 
      protein-DNA complexes, the first localized at the estrogen responsive element of 
      the gene and the second in intron I, thus proving a direct participation of the 
      receptor in these two complexes. The procedure used allows the visualization and 
      rapid localization of specific transcription factors bound in vitro to a promoter 
      or any other gene region.
