VI  - 56
IP  - 8
DP  - 1985 Oct 15
TI  - Bilaterality in familial breast cancer patients.
PG  - 2092-8
AB  - The authors conducted this study to determine the probability of a second primary 
      developing in the contralateral breast of a patient, based on her present age, 
      age at her first breast primary, and family history of breast cancer in her 
      mother, sister, or second-degree relative. The study involved 556 patients. With 
      premenopausal diagnosis of the first primary, the probabilities to the 19th year 
      for the three types of family histories ranged from 35% to 38%; with 
      postmenopausal diagnosis, they ranged from 11% to 26%. The probability for all 
      familial patients was 28%. This contrasts with a probability of 13% reported for 
      a general series of patients. An early age at diagnosis and family history of the 
      disease thus have important enhancing effects on the development of second 
      primaries. This information could be useful to physicians in deciding how best to 
      manage the treatment of their patients.
