VI  - 50
IP  - 13
DP  - 1990 Jul 1
TI  - Radiosensitivity of skin fibroblasts from atomic bomb survivors with and without 
      breast cancer.
PG  - 4050-5
AB  - Fibroblasts were established in vitro from skin biopsies obtained from 55 women 
      and 1 man with or without breast cancer and with or without exposure to radiation 
      from the atomic bomb explosion in Hiroshima. The radiosensitivity of these cells 
      was evaluated by clonogenic assays after exposure to X-rays or to fission 
      neutrons from a 252Cf source. Data were fitted to a multitarget model, S/S0 = A 
      [1 - (1 - ekD)N], for both X-ray and neutron dose-survival curves. A single hit 
      model, S/S0 = AekD, fits the neutron dose-survival responses as well. There were 
      no differences in the means or variances of radiosensitivity between exposed and 
      nonexposed groups or between patients with or without breast cancer. Hence, 
      although the sample is not large, it provides no support for the hypothesis that 
      atomic bomb radiation preferentially induces breast cancer in women whose cells 
      in vitro are sensitive to cell killing by radiation.
