VI  - 265
IP  - 34
DP  - 1990 Dec 5
TI  - Role of insulin-like growth factors and the type I insulin-like growth factor 
      receptor in the estrogen-stimulated proliferation of human breast cancer cells.
PG  - 21172-8
AB  - Estrogen sensitizes the MCF-7 estrogen-responsive breast cancer cell line to the 
      mitogenic effect of insulin and the insulin-like growth factors (IGFs). This 
      sensitization is specific for estrogen and occurs at physiological concentrations 
      of estradiol. Dose-response experiments with insulin, IGF-I, and IGF-II suggested 
      that the sensitization is mediated through the type I IGF receptor. Binding 
      experiments with 125I-IGF-I and hybridization of a type I IGF receptor probe to 
      RNA showed that the levels of the type I IGF receptor and its mRNA are increased 
      7- and 6.5-fold, respectively, by estradiol. IGF-I and estradiol had similar 
      synergistic effects on other estrogen-responsive breast cancer cell lines, but 
      IGF-I alone increased the proliferation of the MDA MB-231 cell line which is not 
      responsive to estrogens. These experiments suggest that an important mechanism by 
      which estrogens stimulate the proliferation of hormone-dependent breast cancer 
      cells involves sensitization to the proliferative effects of IGFs and that this 
      may involve regulation of the type I IGF receptor.
