VI  - 6
IP  - 2
DP  - 1989 May
TI  - Oncogene structure, function, and expression in breast cancer.
PG  - 110-25
AB  - The research of the past decade has made it clear that aberrant expression of 
      genes that encode growth factors, their receptors, and other genes involved in 
      normal cell growth and differentiation--so-called oncogenes--play important roles 
      in determining the proliferative and invasive characteristics of malignant 
      mammary neoplasms. The authors briefly review the topic of oncogenes and the 
      relevance of oncogenes to breast carcinoma; also included is a description of 
      current techniques commonly employed in the study of aberrant oncogene structure 
      and function. Also presented is the authors' own work on oncogene expression in 
      breast neoplasms, which implicates the neu, fms, PDGF-A and Ki-ras oncogenes in 
      the control of mammary epithelial cell proliferation by autocrine and paracrine 
      mechanisms.
