VI  - 12
IP  - 1
DP  - 1985 Spring
TI  - Impact of breast self-examination planned educational messages on social network 
      communications: an exploratory study.
PG  - 51-64
AB  - This two-part study examined the effect of college women's participation in a 
      breast self-examination (BSE) educational program on discussion of BSE with 
      specific members of their social network. In addition, the characteristics of 
      college women who did report discussion with others were investigated as was the 
      relationship between this discussion and the participants' mothers' breast cancer 
      screening behaviors. Results suggest that a BSE education intervention which 
      includes explicit messages to encourage discussion with social network members is 
      effective in increasing communication with mothers, sisters and friends. College 
      women who discussed BSE with their mothers were more likely to have mothers who 
      have a high quality BSE practice and who state an intention to request a clinical 
      breast examination at their next physician visit. The limitations of this study 
      are discussed with recommendations for future research.
