DP  - 1990
TI  - Enhanced expression and secretion of an epithelial membrane antigen (MA5) in a 
      human mucinous breast tumor line (BT549).
PG  - 145-57
AB  - The mouse monoclonal antibody MA5, generated versus a membrane-enriched extract 
      of breast cancer metastatic to liver, detects one or two high molecular weight 
      species (greater than 200 kD) in breast tumor membranes, human milk fat globule 
      membranes, and various breast tumor cell lines. From comparative studies of five 
      breast carcinoma lines (BT20, BT549, MCF-7, T47D, and ZR75-1), as well as an 
      epithelial line established from milk (HBL-100), we report the stimulation of 
      expression of MA5-reactive antigen in a mucinous breast tumor cell line (BT549) 
      through the use of a culture medium supplemented with charcoal-absorbed fetal 
      calf serum, insulin, and hydrocortisone. Large amounts of aggregated MA5-reactive 
      antigen are secreted into the culture medium and can be recovered from the media 
      for further purification by centrifugation. These findings suggest that BT549 
      cells, grown in the special nutritive medium, may be useful in providing an ample 
      source of epithelial membrane antigen (also termed polymorphic epithelial mucin) 
      for standardization of clinical assay protocols, as well as provide a model 
      system for studies of the regulation of expression for this class of antigens in 
      breast carcinoma.
